{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fb71b8d6-dcb5-4abc-9edc-1b9ce016257f","content":"## What Changed\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, **implicit span conversions** participate more aggressively in overload resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)\n```\n\nover the old resolution:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\nbecause `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is now a valid (and preferred) implicit conversion. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be captured in expression trees — so the expression tree fails.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nDisambiguate by forcing the `Enumerable` overload. Either call it as a static method or cast the array:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: explicit static call\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n\n// Option 2: cast to IEnumerable<int> so the old overload wins\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nBoth ensure the compiler binds to `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`, which is expression-tree–safe.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e21fdf4e-824a-42ed-958a-0d95ff91dc8f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's been a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe most likely culprit is a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays in .NET 10 — it might now prefer a different overload or extension method than it did in earlier versions, which would cause the expression tree compilation to behave differently when interpreted versus compiled. and `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` becomes the preferred overload since `T[]` can now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. The issue is that `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` are ref structs, which can't be used in expression trees—so when the compiler binds `.Contains()` to a span-based method, the expression tree compilation fails because that method signature can't be represented in an expression tree.\n\nActually, I need to think through the timeline more carefully. The implicit span conversions and how they affect overload resolution changed across C# versions, particularly between C# 13 and C# 14, so the root cause might be tied to when these conversion rules shifted.\n\nThe real issue is probably that in C# 14, the compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` because `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is considered a more specific match than `IEnumerable<T>`. But when this method call ends up in an expression tree, the interpreter can't handle the ref struct parameter, causing the runtime failure. I'm realizing the issue might be that C# 14 now prefers the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` overload due to implicit span conversions, which causes a compile-time error in expression trees since ref structs aren't allowed—but the user says it throws at runtime, so maybe the compiler still falls back to `Enumerable.Contains` for expression trees while something about `.NET 10`'s runtime behavior changed. I'm wondering if the compiler might still resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` in expression tree contexts since the span-based overload isn't valid there, which would mean no breaking change. Or perhaps the runtime behavior of `Enumerable.Contains` itself changed in .NET 10, or the user is actually seeing a compile-time error but describing it as a runtime issue.\n\nLet me approach this from the actual breaking changes in C# 14 and .NET 10. The most relevant one is the refinement of first-class span support and implicit span conversions that started in C# 13. With the `params` span feature and improved overload resolution, the compiler might now prefer span-based overloads in situations where it previously wouldn't, and this could have been the source of the breaking change even back in .NET 9.\n\nWhat I'm realizing is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` for `ReadOnlySpan<T>` has existed for years, and so has `Enumerable.Contains` for `IEnumerable<T>`. Before C# 13, calling `Contains` on an array would resolve to the LINQ version because there was no implicit conversion from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` in overload resolution. But with the span improvements in C# 13 and 14, that implicit conversion is now considered, which means the span-based overload could win instead. Span conversions are treated as worse than reference conversions in overload resolution for backward compatibility, so `Enumerable.Contains` would normally win. But C# 14 might have changed this tiebreaking rule, causing `MemoryExtensions.Contains` to be preferred instead—though I'm not entirely certain about the exact mechanism behind this change.\n\nSince `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct and expression trees can't contain ref struct operations, this would either cause a compile-time error or fail at runtime. The workaround is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the reference conversion path.\n\nBut wait—if this is an expression tree lambda, the compiler should catch ref struct issues at compile time, not runtime. Unless the user is manually constructing the expression tree with `Expression.Call`, which could defer the error. Given that they mention it throws at runtime, I'm wondering if there's a version difference at play here—maybe .NET 9 resolved this differently tha